\f1\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 What is CouchDB - HTTP API?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs30 \cf0 \cb3 With HTTP request headers, you can interact with CouchDB. Using these requests we can retrieve data from the database, store data in to the database in the form of documents, and we can see as well as format we can the documents that are stored in a database.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 \cb3 HTTP Request Formats\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf0 \cb3 While interacting with the database we will employvarious request formats such as get, head, post, put, delete, and copy. For all operations in CouchDB, both the input datastructures and the output data structures would be in the form of JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) object.\cb1 \
\cb3 Below are the various request formats of HTTP Protocol employed to interact with CouchDB.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0
\b\fs32 \cf0 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
GET
\b0  \uc0\u8722  This format is employedto get a specific item. To get different items, you have to send specific url patterns. In CouchDBwith this GET request, we can get static items, database documents and configuration, and statistical information in the form of JSON documents (in most cases).\cb1 \
\ls11\ilvl0
\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
HEAD
\b0  \uc0\u8722  The HEAD method is employedto get the HTTP header of a GET request without the body of the response.\cb1 \
\ls11\ilvl0
\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
POST
\b0  \uc0\u8722  Post request is employed to upload data. In CouchDBwith POST request, you can set values, upload documents, set document values, and can also beginspecific administration commands.\cb1 \
\ls11\ilvl0
\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
PUT
\b0  \uc0\u8722  With PUT request, you can create new objects, databases, documents, views and design documents.\cb1 \
\ls11\ilvl0
\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
DELETE
\b0  \uc0\u8722  With DELETE request, you can delete documents, views, and design documents.\cb1 \
\ls11\ilvl0
\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
COPY
\b0  \uc0\u8722  With COPY method, you can copy documents and objects.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 \cb3 HTTP Request Headers\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf0 \cb3 HTTP headers must be supplied to get the correct format and encoding. during sending the request to the CouchDB server, you can send Http request headers including with the request. Below are the different Http request headers.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\b\fs32 \cf0 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Content-type
\b0  \uc0\u8722  This Header is employed for specifying the content type of the data that we provide to the server along with the request. Mostly the type of the content we send including with the request will be MIME type or JSON (application/json). With Content-type on a request is highly recommended.\cb1 \
\ls12\ilvl0
\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Accept
\b0  \uc0\u8722  Accept header is employedfor specifying the server, the list of data types that client can understand, so that the server will send its response with those data types. Generally here, you can send the list of MIME data types the client accepts, partitioned by colons.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf0 \cb3 Even though, with Accept in queries of CouchDB is not needed, it is highly recommended to make sure that the data returned can be processed by the client.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 \cb3 Response Headers\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf0 \cb3 Response headers are the headers of the response that is sent by the server. These headers give information regarding the content that is send by the server as response.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls13\ilvl0
\b\fs32 \cf0 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Content-type
\b0  \uc0\u8722  This header specifies the MIME type of the data returned by the server. For most request, the returned MIME type is text/plain.\cb1 \
\ls13\ilvl0
\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Cache-control
\b0  \uc0\u8722  This header suggests the client about treating the information sent by the server. CouchDB mostly returns the must-revalidate, which indicates that the information should be revalidated if possible.\cb1 \
\ls13\ilvl0
\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Content-length
\b0  \uc0\u8722  This header returns the length of the content sent by the server, in bytes.\cb1 \
\ls13\ilvl0
\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Etag
\b0  \uc0\u8722  This header is used to show the revision for a document, or a view.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

